const e=[{id:1,surah:"Al-Mujadila",surahAr:"المجادلة",surahNum:58,ayahRef:"58:1",ayahAr:"قَدْ سَمِعَ اللَّهُ قَوْلَ الَّتِي تُجَادِلُكَ فِي زَوْجِهَا وَتَشْتَكِي إِلَى اللَّهِ وَاللَّهُ يَسْمَعُ تَحَاوُرَكُمَا",ayahEn:"Certainly has Allah heard the speech of the one who argues with you concerning her husband and directs her complaint to Allah. And Allah hears your dialogue; indeed, Allah is Hearing and Seeing.",ayahUr:"بیشک اللہ نے اُس عورت کی بات سُن لی جو اپنے شوہر کے بارے میں آپ سے بحث کرتی ہے اور اللہ سے فریاد کرتی ہے۔",companion:"Khawla bint Tha'laba",companionAr:"خولة بنت ثعلبة",companionRel:"A Muslim woman whose husband Aws ibn al-Samit pronounced zihar (a pre-Islamic divorce formula)",story:`Khawla bint Tha'laba's husband Aws ibn al-Samit said to her "You are to me like my mother's back" (zihar), an ancient Arab form of divorce. She came to the Prophet ﷺ in deep distress, arguing her case repeatedly while he replied that there was no ruling yet. Aisha (رضي الله عنها) later said: "Blessed is Allah Whose hearing encompasses all things. I heard her from behind a curtain yet Allah revealed from above the seven heavens that He heard her." The entire first section of Surah Al-Mujadila (58:1–4) descended, establishing zihar as haram and creating a kaffara (expiation) to allow the couple to reconcile.`,companionResponse:'Khawla wept with joy upon hearing the revelation and said: "Alhamdulillah! My supplication has been answered." She and Aws were permitted to remain married after he performed kaffara.',source:"Ibn Maja 2063; Musnad Ahmad 27490; Tafsir al-Tabari under 58:1",category:"legal"},{id:2,surah:"Abasa",surahAr:"عبس",surahNum:80,ayahRef:"80:1–10",ayahAr:"عَبَسَ وَتَوَلَّىٰ • أَن جَاءَهُ الْأَعْمَىٰ • وَمَا يُدْرِيكَ لَعَلَّهُ يَزَّكَّىٰ",ayahEn:"He frowned and turned away — because there came to him the blind man. But what would make you perceive, [O Muhammad], that perhaps he might be purified?",ayahUr:"اس نے منہ پھیرا اور تیوری چڑھائی — کہ وہ نابینا اُس کے پاس آیا — تجھے کیا معلوم شاید وہ پاک ہو جاتا؟",companion:"Abdullah ibn Umm Maktum",companionAr:"عبد الله ابن أم مكتوم",companionRel:"A blind companion and early convert from Mecca; later appointed twice as acting governor of Medina",story:`Abdullah ibn Umm Maktum, blind from birth, interrupted the Prophet ﷺ while he was engaged in da'wa with a group of Quraysh chieftains whom he hoped to convert — among them Abu Jahl, al-Walid ibn al-Mughira, and Umayya ibn Khalaf. He repeatedly called out "Teach me from what Allah has taught you!" The Prophet ﷺ was briefly displeased and turned away. Allah immediately revealed these ten ayahs rebuking the Prophet ﷺ and elevating the status of the sincere seeker over the arrogant nobleman. It is one of the very rare ayahs that openly correct the Prophet ﷺ — a testament to the Quran's divine, uncensored honesty.`,companionResponse:'Ibn Umm Maktum was deeply honoured by the revelation. The Prophet ﷺ subsequently always welcomed him warmly, saying "Welcome to the one on whose account my Lord rebuked me."',source:"Tirmidhi 3331; Tafsir Ibn Kathir under 80:1; Seerah Ibn Hisham Vol. 2",category:"personal"},{id:3,surah:"Al-Nur",surahAr:"النور",surahNum:24,ayahRef:"24:11–20",ayahAr:"إِنَّ الَّذِينَ جَاءُوا بِالْإِفْكِ عُصْبَةٌ مِّنكُمْ ۚ لَا تَحْسَبُوهُ شَرًّا لَّكُم ۖ بَلْ هُوَ خَيْرٌ لَّكُمْ",ayahEn:"Indeed, those who came with falsehood are a group among you. Do not think it bad for you; rather it is good for you.",ayahUr:"بے شک جو لوگ یہ بہتان لائے ہیں وہ تم میں سے ایک گروہ ہے — اسے اپنے لیے بُرا نہ سمجھو بلکہ یہ تمہارے لیے بھلائی ہے۔",companion:"Aisha bint Abi Bakr",companionAr:"عائشة بنت أبي بكر",companionRel:"Wife of the Prophet ﷺ; Umm al-Mu'mineen (Mother of the Believers)",story:`In 5 AH during the return from the Banu al-Mustaliq expedition, Aisha (رضي الله عنها) was accidentally left behind when her litter-bearers assumed she was inside. Safwan ibn al-Mu'attal found her and escorted her to Medina, arriving after the army. The hypocrite Abdullah ibn Ubayy spread slanderous rumours across Medina for nearly a month. Even Ali cautiously told the Prophet ﷺ "Women are plenty; you can replace her." Aisha fell ill with grief and wept for days. At last, while she sat with her parents and had accepted whatever decree Allah willed, the revelation descended — 10 ayahs declaring her absolute innocence, establishing the law of qadhf (false accusation), and warning all of Medina.`,companionResponse:'Aisha said: "I had expected Allah to send a dream to the Prophet ﷺ to clear me, but I never imagined He would reveal Quran about me that would be recited until the Day of Judgement." Her father Abu Bakr wept uncontrollably.',source:"Bukhari 4141; Muslim 2770; Seerah Ibn Hisham (The Affair of the Necklace)",category:"social"},{id:4,surah:"Al-Hujurat",surahAr:"الحجرات",surahNum:49,ayahRef:"49:2",ayahAr:"يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا لَا تَرْفَعُوا أَصْوَاتَكُمْ فَوْقَ صَوْتِ النَّبِيِّ",ayahEn:"O you who have believed, do not raise your voices above the voice of the Prophet or be loud to him in speech like the loudness of some of you to others, lest your deeds become worthless while you perceive not.",ayahUr:"اے ایمان والو! اپنی آوازیں نبی کی آواز سے اُونچی مت کرو۔",companion:"Thabit ibn Qays ibn al-Shamma's",companionAr:"ثابت بن قيس بن شماس",companionRel:"The official orator (khatib) of the Ansar of Medina; known for his powerful voice",story:`Thabit ibn Qays was famed for his booming voice, which he used eloquently as the Prophet's spokesman. After 49:2 was revealed — instructing believers not to raise their voices above the Prophet ﷺ — Thabit was shattered. He locked himself in his home, ceased attending the mosque, and told companions who inquired: "I am a man of Hell-fire! My voice has always been loud; I fear my deeds are nullified!" The Prophet ﷺ, noticing his absence, sent Sa'd ibn Mu'adh to check on him. When informed, the Prophet ﷺ said: "Tell him he is not among the people of Hell-fire but among the people of Paradise."`,companionResponse:"Thabit ibn Qays returned to the community reassured. He was later martyred at the Battle of Yamama (12 AH), dying with the same courageous voice, shouting in battle until his last breath.",source:"Bukhari 4846; Muslim 119; Tafsir al-Qurtubi under 49:2",category:"personal"},{id:5,surah:"An-Nisa",surahAr:"النساء",surahNum:4,ayahRef:"4:95",ayahAr:"لَّا يَسْتَوِي الْقَاعِدُونَ مِنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ غَيْرُ أُولِي الضَّرَرِ وَالْمُجَاهِدُونَ فِي سَبِيلِ اللَّهِ",ayahEn:"Not equal are those believers who remain at home — other than the disabled — and those who strive in the cause of Allah with their wealth and their lives.",ayahUr:"برابر نہیں ہیں وہ مؤمن جو گھر بیٹھے رہتے ہیں — سوائے معذوروں کے — اور جو اللہ کی راہ میں جہاد کرتے ہیں۔",companion:"Abdullah ibn Umm Maktum",companionAr:"عبد الله ابن أم مكتوم",companionRel:"Blind companion; early Meccan convert",story:`When 4:95 was first revealed saying "Not equal are those who sit at home and those who strive in Allah's cause," the blind Abdullah ibn Umm Maktum exclaimed: "O Messenger of Allah! If I could fight, I would fight!" He was deeply distressed at the implication that sitting home made him inferior. The Prophet ﷺ, who was with Zayd ibn Thabit at the time, paused in mid-revelation — his thigh (which was on Zayd's thigh) became very heavy, pressing Zayd down. Then the remaining clause was added: "...other than those who have a disability (ghayr uli al-darar)." This exemption was revealed specifically in response to Ibn Umm Maktum's earnest plea.`,companionResponse:"Ibn Umm Maktum was reassured and continued in full service. He eventually participated in the Battle of al-Qadisiyya despite his blindness, holding the banner and refusing to stay behind.",source:"Bukhari 2832; Tirmidhi 3033; Musnad Ahmad 21812",category:"warfare"},{id:6,surah:"Al-Ahzab",surahAr:"الأحزاب",surahNum:33,ayahRef:"33:37",ayahAr:"وَإِذْ تَقُولُ لِلَّذِي أَنْعَمَ اللَّهُ عَلَيْهِ وَأَنْعَمْتَ عَلَيْهِ أَمْسِكْ عَلَيْكَ زَوْجَكَ وَاتَّقِ اللَّهَ",ayahEn:'And when you said to the one on whom Allah bestowed favour and you bestowed favour: "Keep your wife and fear Allah," while you concealed within yourself what Allah was to disclose.',ayahUr:"اور جب تم نے اس شخص سے کہا جس پر اللہ نے اور تم نے انعام کیا تھا کہ اپنی بیوی کو روکے رکھو اور اللہ سے ڈرو۔",companion:"Zayd ibn Haritha",companionAr:"زيد بن حارثة",companionRel:"Freed slave and adopted son of the Prophet ﷺ; the only companion named by name in the Quran",story:"Zayd ibn Haritha was the Prophet's beloved freed slave whom he adopted. The Prophet ﷺ arranged for Zayd to marry Zaynab bint Jahsh (a Qurayshi noblewoman). Their temperaments clashed, and Zayd came repeatedly to the Prophet ﷺ expressing his desire to divorce her. The Prophet ﷺ — knowing a divine plan was unfolding to abolish the Arab custom that treated adopted sons as biological sons — advised Zayd to keep his wife. When Zayd ultimately divorced Zaynab, Allah commanded the Prophet ﷺ to marry her, which he did. This ayah, and surrounding verses, permanently abolished the Arab prohibition on marrying a divorced wife of one's adopted son.",companionResponse:"Zayd remained one of the most beloved companions to the Prophet ﷺ. He was appointed commander of the Mu'ta expedition in 8 AH — the highest military honour — where he was martyred. The Prophet ﷺ wept publicly at his death.",source:"Bukhari 7421; Tafsir Ibn Kathir 33:37; Seerah Ibn Hisham (Marriage of Zaynab)",category:"family"},{id:7,surah:"At-Tawbah",surahAr:"التوبة",surahNum:9,ayahRef:"9:113",ayahAr:"مَا كَانَ لِلنَّبِيِّ وَالَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَن يَسْتَغْفِرُوا لِلْمُشْرِكِينَ وَلَوْ كَانُوا أُولِي قُرْبَىٰ",ayahEn:"It is not for the Prophet and those who have believed to ask forgiveness for the polytheists, even if they were relatives, after it has become clear to them that they are companions of Hellfire.",ayahUr:"نبی اور ایمان والوں کو جائز نہیں کہ مشرکوں کے لیے دعائے مغفرت کریں اگرچہ وہ رشتے دار ہوں۔",companion:"Ali ibn Abi Talib",companionAr:"علي بن أبي طالب",companionRel:"Cousin and son-in-law of the Prophet ﷺ; fourth Caliph",story:`Ali ibn Abi Talib asked the Prophet ﷺ whether he had sought forgiveness for his pagan mother Fatima bint Asad who had raised the Prophet with great care. The Prophet ﷺ replied that he had, and mentioned he had sought forgiveness for Abu Talib (his uncle and protector) as well. Subsequently this ayah was revealed, prohibiting seeking forgiveness for polytheists. Some narrations relate it specifically to the Prophet's grief over Abu Talib, who protected him throughout his Meccan mission but died without embracing Islam. The Prophet ﷺ reportedly said: "I will keep seeking forgiveness for you until I am forbidden," — and this ayah was the divine response.`,companionResponse:"Ali was moved and accepted the ruling. He noted that the Prophet ﷺ showed the same obedience to revelation concerning his most beloved relatives that he showed in all matters.",source:"Muslim 976; Bukhari 1360; Tafsir al-Tabari 9:113",category:"doctrinal"},{id:8,surah:"Al-Anfal",surahAr:"الأنفال",surahNum:8,ayahRef:"8:1",ayahAr:"يَسْأَلُونَكَ عَنِ الْأَنفَالِ ۖ قُلِ الْأَنفَالُ لِلَّهِ وَالرَّسُولِ ۖ فَاتَّقُوا اللَّهَ وَأَصْلِحُوا ذَاتَ بَيْنِكُمْ",ayahEn:"They ask you about the bounties of war. Say: The bounties of war belong to Allah and the Messenger. So fear Allah and amend that which is between you and obey Allah and His Messenger, if you should be believers.",ayahUr:"وہ آپ سے غنیمت کے بارے میں پوچھتے ہیں۔ فرمادیجیے کہ غنیمت اللہ اور رسول کی ہے۔",companion:"Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas (and the Companions of Badr)",companionAr:"سعد بن أبي وقاص وأصحاب بدر",companionRel:"One of the Ten Promised Paradise; commander at Qadisiyya",story:`After the Battle of Badr (2 AH/624 CE) — Islam's first major victory — a heated dispute arose among the companions over how to divide the captured war spoils (anfal). The front-line fighters said "We earned it by fighting." Those who guarded the Prophet's position said "We protected the Prophet." The cavalry argued their share was higher. Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas reportedly had a dispute that almost led to a sword-fight. The entire first section of Surah Al-Anfal was revealed to resolve this, placing all war booty under divine and prophetic authority, giving one-fifth (khums) to Allah's prescribed categories and the rest equally among fighters.`,companionResponse:`Sa'd accepted the ruling. Decades later, as the victor of al-Qadisiyya, he faithfully applied the same khums rules to the enormous Persian treasury, sending the famous "jewels of Kisra" to Umar in Medina.`,source:"Abu Dawud 2737; Tirmidhi 3079; Musnad Ahmad 1645",category:"warfare"},{id:9,surah:"Al-Baqarah",surahAr:"البقرة",surahNum:2,ayahRef:"2:158",ayahAr:"إِنَّ الصَّفَا وَالْمَرْوَةَ مِن شَعَائِرِ اللَّهِ ۖ فَمَنْ حَجَّ الْبَيْتَ أَوِ اعْتَمَرَ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَيْهِ أَن يَطَّوَّفَ بِهِمَا",ayahEn:"Indeed, al-Safa and al-Marwa are among the symbols of Allah. So whoever makes Hajj to the House or performs 'umra — there is no blame upon him for walking between them.",ayahUr:"بے شک صفا اور مروہ اللہ کی نشانیوں میں سے ہیں۔ پس جو شخص بیت اللہ کا حج یا عمرہ کرے اس پر ان کے درمیان چکر لگانے میں کوئی گناہ نہیں۔",companion:"Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas (as asked on behalf of Ansar)",companionAr:"سعد بن أبي وقاص",companionRel:"Companion; Uncle of the Prophet ﷺ through maternal lineage",story:"The Ansar of Medina had previously been accustomed to walking between Safa and Marwa in veneration of the idol Isaf (placed on Safa) and Na'ila (placed on Marwa). After Islam, they feared that sa'y (the walk between the two hills) might be considered pagan, so they were reluctant to perform it even after it was part of Hajj and Umra. Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas (in some narrations, Urwa ibn Zubayr asking Aisha) posed the question to the Prophet ﷺ. This ayah then confirmed that walking between Safa and Marwa is not only permitted but is a shar'i obligation (wajib according to Shafi'i and Hanbali schools).",companionResponse:`Aisha, who is reported in Bukhari to have explained the background, said: "This ayah was not meant to indicate that it was optional; otherwise it would have said 'there is no blame if he does NOT walk.'" The companions understood that sa'y was obligatory.`,source:"Bukhari 1643; Muslim 1277; Tafsir al-Qurtubi 2:158",category:"worship"},{id:10,surah:"Al-Baqarah",surahAr:"البقرة",surahNum:2,ayahRef:"2:222",ayahAr:"وَيَسْأَلُونَكَ عَنِ الْمَحِيضِ ۖ قُلْ هُوَ أَذًى فَاعْتَزِلُوا النِّسَاءَ فِي الْمَحِيضِ",ayahEn:"And they ask you about menstruation. Say: It is harm, so keep away from wives during menstruation.",ayahUr:"اور وہ آپ سے حیض کے بارے میں پوچھتے ہیں۔ فرمادیجیے کہ وہ ایذا ہے پس حیض کے دنوں میں عورتوں سے الگ رہو۔",companion:"Anas ibn Malik (relaying the question from the Ansar)",companionAr:"أنس بن مالك",companionRel:"Personal servant of the Prophet ﷺ; served him for 10 years",story:"The Ansar of Medina asked the Prophet ﷺ about the pre-Islamic practice regarding menstruating women. The Arabs of Jahiliyya had two extremes: some completely isolated menstruating women from the home (like the Jews), while others had no restrictions at all. Anas ibn Malik relayed the Ansar's confusion to the Prophet ﷺ. This ayah was revealed establishing the moderate Islamic ruling: marital intercourse is prohibited during menstruation, but all other forms of companionship, eating together, and sharing the home are perfectly permissible.",companionResponse:'The Ansar fully embraced the ruling. Anas ibn Malik later transmitted this hadith extensively, noting the Prophet ﷺ said: "Do everything except intercourse." The Jewish community in Medina reportedly said this ruling was more humane than their own practice.',source:"Muslim 302; Tirmidhi 2977; Musnad Ahmad 11561",category:"legal"},{id:11,surah:"An-Nisa",surahAr:"النساء",surahNum:4,ayahRef:"4:7–12",ayahAr:"لِّلرِّجَالِ نَصِيبٌ مِّمَّا تَرَكَ الْوَالِدَانِ وَالْأَقْرَبُونَ وَلِلنِّسَاءِ نَصِيبٌ",ayahEn:"For men is a share of what the parents and close relatives leave, and for women is a share of what the parents and close relatives leave, be it little or much — an obligatory share.",ayahUr:"مردوں کے لیے اس میں سے حصہ ہے جو ماں باپ اور قریبی رشتے دار چھوڑ جائیں اور عورتوں کے لیے بھی حصہ ہے۔",companion:"Aws ibn Thabit al-Ansari's family",companionAr:"عيال أوس بن ثابت الأنصاري",companionRel:"Aws ibn Thabit was an Ansari companion whose widow and daughters were dispossessed by his male relatives",story:`When Aws ibn Thabit al-Ansari died in battle, his two brothers Suwayid and 'Arfaja (following pre-Islamic Arab custom) seized all his property, leaving nothing for his wife Umm Kuhha and their young daughters. She came to the Prophet ﷺ saying: "My daughters' father died as a martyr; his cousins have taken all his property and left nothing for us." Pre-Islamic Arabs gave inheritance only to male warriors. Allah revealed the Islamic inheritance laws (4:7–12) which, for the first time in Arabian history, guaranteed fixed shares for daughters, widows, and all heirs — male and female.`,companionResponse:"The Prophet ﷺ summoned Suwayid and 'Arfaja, declared the revelation, and ordered them to return the property and distribute it according to the new law. The two daughters received their inheritance. Umm Kuhha received her share as widow. This became the foundation of Islamic inheritance law ('ilm al-fara'id).",source:"Abu Dawud 2891; Tirmidhi 2092; Musnad Ahmad 22352",category:"legal"},{id:12,surah:"Ali Imran",surahAr:"آل عمران",surahNum:3,ayahRef:"3:128",ayahAr:"لَيْسَ لَكَ مِنَ الْأَمْرِ شَيْءٌ أَوْ يَتُوبَ عَلَيْهِمْ أَوْ يُعَذِّبَهُمْ فَإِنَّهُمْ ظَالِمُونَ",ayahEn:"Not for you is the decision whether He should accept their repentance or punish them, for indeed, they are wrongdoers.",ayahUr:"آپ کو اس معاملے میں کوئی اختیار نہیں — خواہ اللہ ان کی توبہ قبول کرے یا انہیں عذاب دے۔",companion:"Umar ibn al-Khattab (and the Prophet ﷺ himself)",companionAr:"عمر بن الخطاب",companionRel:"Second Caliph; closest adviser to the Prophet ﷺ",story:`At the Battle of Uhud (3 AH), the Prophet ﷺ was severely wounded — his tooth broken, his face cut, blood pouring down. In a moment of human pain, he made a du'a against the Quraysh who had harmed him. Some narrations state he prayed: "O Allah, guide my people for they do not know." Others note he lamented the injury loudly, saying "How can a people who have done this to their Prophet succeed?" Umar was burning with rage at those who had injured the Prophet ﷺ. This ayah came, reminding both the Prophet ﷺ and Umar that vengeance, guidance, and mercy all belong to Allah alone — not to any human, however righteous.`,companionResponse:"Umar later said this ayah completely redirected his fury. Abu Sufyan, who had wounded the Prophet ﷺ at Uhud, embraced Islam 7 years later at the Conquest of Mecca — a fulfillment of the ayah's message that repentance was possible.",source:"Bukhari 4069; Muslim 1791; Tafsir al-Tabari 3:128",category:"warfare"},{id:13,surah:"At-Tahrim",surahAr:"التحريم",surahNum:66,ayahRef:"66:1",ayahAr:"يَا أَيُّهَا النَّبِيُّ لِمَ تُحَرِّمُ مَا أَحَلَّ اللَّهُ لَكَ ۖ تَبْتَغِي مَرْضَاتَ أَزْوَاجِكَ",ayahEn:"O Prophet, why do you prohibit yourself what Allah has made lawful for you, seeking the approval of your wives? And Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.",ayahUr:"اے نبی! آپ نے وہ چیز کیوں حرام کر لی جو اللہ نے آپ کے لیے حلال کی ہے؟ آپ اپنی بیویوں کی خوشنودی چاہتے ہیں؟",companion:"Hafsa bint Umar and Aisha bint Abi Bakr",companionAr:"حفصة بنت عمر وعائشة بنت أبي بكر",companionRel:"Two wives of the Prophet ﷺ; Hafsa was Umar's daughter, Aisha was Abu Bakr's daughter",story:`The Prophet ﷺ habitually visited his wife Hafsa on her "day" (the rotation system among wives). One day he also visited Zaynab bint Jahsh who offered him honey sherbet which he liked very much. Aisha and Hafsa, in a moment of wives' rivalry, conspired together: each would tell him they could smell fenugreek (maghaafir — a notoriously foul-smelling plant) from him. Not wanting to displease his wives, the Prophet ﷺ declared honey forbidden to himself. Allah revealed the opening of Surah At-Tahrim reproving this act and reminding the Prophet ﷺ — and all believers — not to forbid what Allah has made lawful out of human sentiment.`,companionResponse:`The Prophet ﷺ revealed the matter to Hafsa in confidence, but she disclosed it to Aisha. This formed part of the "secret" referenced in 66:3. He later returned to drinking honey. The surah's first 5 ayahs deal entirely with this episode.`,source:"Bukhari 4912; Muslim 1474; Tafsir Ibn Kathir 66:1",category:"family"},{id:14,surah:"Al-Kahf",surahAr:"الكهف",surahNum:18,ayahRef:"18:23–24",ayahAr:"وَلَا تَقُولَنَّ لِشَيْءٍ إِنِّي فَاعِلٌ ذَٰلِكَ غَدًا • إِلَّا أَن يَشَاءَ اللَّهُ",ayahEn:'And never say of anything, "Indeed, I will do that tomorrow" — except [when adding], "If Allah wills." And remember your Lord when you forget.',ayahUr:"اور کبھی کسی بات کے لیے یہ نہ کہو کہ میں کل یہ کام کروں گا — مگر یہ کہو کہ اگر اللہ چاہے۔",companion:"Abdullah ibn Abbas (relaying a question from the Quraysh)",companionAr:"عبد الله بن عباس",companionRel:'Cousin of the Prophet ﷺ; "Tarjuman al-Quran" (Interpreter of the Quran)',story:`The Quraysh of Mecca sent two men — Nadr ibn al-Harith and Uqba ibn Abi Mu'ayt — to the rabbis of Medina to test whether Muhammad ﷺ was a true prophet. The rabbis advised them to ask him about the People of the Cave, the man who wandered the earth, and the soul (ruh). When the Quraysh posed these questions, the Prophet ﷺ — eagerly wishing to answer immediately — said "Come tomorrow and I will tell you." He waited fifteen days without revelation, deeply distressed. Then Surah Al-Kahf was revealed in full. Along with the stories, came 18:23–24 — an eternal correction: never commit to the future without saying "Insha'Allah."`,companionResponse:"Ibn Abbas, who narrated this background, noted that the delay was itself a test and a lesson: the Prophet ﷺ's eagerness to give the Quraysh an answer showed his sincere desire to guide them, and Allah's delay taught him and all believers the adab (etiquette) of acknowledging divine will in all future speech.",source:"Tafsir Ibn Kathir 18:23–24; Tafsir al-Tabari; Seerah Ibn Hisham (Story of the Cave)",category:"doctrinal"},{id:15,surah:"Al-Insan",surahAr:"الإنسان",surahNum:76,ayahRef:"76:8–9",ayahAr:"وَيُطْعِمُونَ الطَّعَامَ عَلَىٰ حُبِّهِ مِسْكِينًا وَيَتِيمًا وَأَسِيرًا • إِنَّمَا نُطْعِمُكُمْ لِوَجْهِ اللَّهِ لَا نُرِيدُ مِنكُمْ جَزَاءً وَلَا شُكُورًا",ayahEn:'And they give food in spite of love for it to the needy, the orphan, and the captive — [Saying]: "We feed you only for the countenance of Allah. We wish not from you reward or gratitude."',ayahUr:"اور وہ خانہ پُری کی محبت کے باوجود مسکین، یتیم اور قیدی کو کھانا کھلاتے ہیں — (کہتے ہیں) ہم تمہیں صرف اللہ کی رضا کے لیے کھلاتے ہیں۔",companion:"Ali ibn Abi Talib, Fatima al-Zahra, Hasan and Husayn",companionAr:"علي بن أبي طالب وفاطمة الزهراء والحسن والحسين",companionRel:"Son-in-law, daughter, and grandsons of the Prophet ﷺ",story:"Hasan and Husayn fell ill and Ali and Fatima (رضي الله عنهم) vowed three days of fasting as kaffara. On each of the three days, when iftar time came, a needy person arrived at their door — first a poor man, then an orphan, then a prisoner. Each time, despite their own days-long fast, they gave away their entire iftar and broke their fast with only water. Allah revealed Surah Al-Insan (or Ad-Dahr) in their honour, immortalising their sacrifice. This surah became one of the most recited in the household of the Prophet ﷺ. Some scholars count this as one of the most beautiful revelation-triggers in all of Quran.",companionResponse:"According to al-Tha'labi's tafsir, the Prophet ﷺ entered upon them on the third day and found them pale and weak from three days of fasting on water alone. He wept and recited 76:8–9 to them — verses describing their own deed as Allah had witnessed it.",source:"Tafsir al-Tha'labi; Al-Hakim in Al-Mustadrak; Ibn Asakir in Tarikh Dimashq",category:"worship"},{id:16,surah:"Al-Mumtahanah",surahAr:"الممتحنة",surahNum:60,ayahRef:"60:10",ayahAr:"يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا جَاءَكُمُ الْمُؤْمِنَاتُ مُهَاجِرَاتٍ فَامْتَحِنُوهُنَّ",ayahEn:"O you who have believed, when the believing women come to you as emigrants, examine them. Allah is most knowing as to their faith.",ayahUr:"اے ایمان والو! جب ایمان والی عورتیں ہجرت کر کے آئیں تو انہیں آزمائو۔",companion:"Umar ibn al-Khattab",companionAr:"عمر بن الخطاب",companionRel:"Second Caliph; one of the Ten Promised Paradise",story:`At the Treaty of Hudaybiyya (6 AH), it was agreed that any Meccan who went to Medina would be returned to Mecca. After the Conquest of Mecca (8 AH), three of Umar ibn al-Khattab's wives who had not yet emigrated remained in Mecca. Two of them accepted Islam and emigrated, but Umar divorced all three before emigrating, saying "I cannot take women I cannot trust." When believing women began emigrating from Mecca to Medina, the question arose: were they to be returned like the men under Hudaybiyya? This ayah clarified that emigrant believing women were to be kept in Medina, examined for their faith, and not returned to the polytheists.`,companionResponse:"Umar remarried Muslim women in Medina. The ayah also established the payment system for Muslim women who emigrated — Medina would pay their Meccan husbands a dowry compensation (mahr) from the treaty fund, showing Islam's extraordinary fairness even to enemies.",source:"Bukhari 2711; Tafsir al-Tabari 60:10; Seerah Ibn Hisham",category:"social"},{id:17,surah:"Al-Masad",surahAr:"المسد",surahNum:111,ayahRef:"111:1–5",ayahAr:"تَبَّتْ يَدَا أَبِي لَهَبٍ وَتَبَّ • مَا أَغْنَىٰ عَنْهُ مَالُهُ وَمَا كَسَبَ",ayahEn:"May the hands of Abu Lahab be ruined, and ruined is he. His wealth will not avail him or that which he gained. He will burn in a Fire of blazing flame.",ayahUr:"ابو لہب کے دونوں ہاتھ ٹوٹ جائیں اور وہ خود بھی تباہ ہو جائے! اس کا مال اور جو کچھ اس نے کمایا کام نہ آیا۔",companion:"Abu Lahab (Abd al-Uzza ibn Abd al-Muttalib) — the anti-companion",companionAr:"أبو لهب عبد العزى بن عبد المطلب",companionRel:"Uncle of the Prophet ﷺ; his most vicious opponent in Mecca",story:'When Allah commanded the Prophet ﷺ "Warn your nearest kin," he climbed Mount Safa and called each clan of Quraysh by name: "O Banu Fihr! O Banu Adi!" until they all gathered. He then said: "If I told you an enemy army was preparing to attack you from behind this mountain, would you believe me?" They said "Yes — we have never known you to lie." He then said: "Then I warn you of a severe punishment before you." Abu Lahab (his own uncle) stood up and said: "May you perish! Is this why you gathered us?" This surah was revealed immediately, naming Abu Lahab directly — an unprecedented move in the Quran.',companionResponse:"Abu Lahab's wife Umm Jamil (sister of Abu Sufyan) went looking for the Prophet ﷺ at the Ka'ba, carrying stones and reciting poetry of insult. She was told by Abu Bakr that the Prophet ﷺ was sitting right there — but she was miraculously unable to see him. Abu Lahab died in Mecca in 2 AH, 7 days after the Battle of Badr, from a skin disease called 'adasa — fulfilled by the surah.",source:"Bukhari 4971; Muslim 208; Tafsir Ibn Kathir 111:1",category:"doctrinal"},{id:18,surah:"Al-Ahzab",surahAr:"الأحزاب",surahNum:33,ayahRef:"33:53",ayahAr:"يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا لَا تَدْخُلُوا بُيُوتَ النَّبِيِّ إِلَّا أَن يُؤْذَنَ لَكُمْ",ayahEn:"O you who have believed, do not enter the houses of the Prophet except when you are permitted for a meal, without awaiting its readiness. But when you are invited, then enter.",ayahUr:"اے ایمان والو! نبی کے گھروں میں بغیر اجازت کے داخل نہ ہو۔",companion:"Anas ibn Malik (reporting on behalf of the household)",companionAr:"أنس بن مالك",companionRel:"Personal servant of the Prophet ﷺ for 10 years; an eye-witness to the event",story:`At the Prophet's wedding celebration with Zaynab bint Jahsh (after Zayd's divorce), some companions stayed excessively long after eating, chatting while the Prophet ﷺ waited patiently to be alone with his new wife. Anas ibn Malik, who served as attendant, narrated: "I saw the Prophet ﷺ hint several times that they should leave but they did not. I could see the embarrassment on his face." The Prophet ﷺ then left, went to his other wives' rooms, and returned — still finding guests. Only then was 33:53 revealed, establishing the "Hijab Verse" — governing entry into prophetic homes and interaction with his wives.`,companionResponse:`Anas said: "This verse was revealed on my account, as I was the one observing how distressed the Prophet ﷺ was." The ruling became the basis for Islamic social etiquette: seeking permission before entering any home, not overstaying one's welcome, and speaking to women of knowledge from behind a screen.`,source:"Bukhari 4791; Muslim 1428; Tafsir al-Suyuti in Al-Dur al-Manthur",category:"social"},{id:19,surah:"Al-Baqarah",surahAr:"البقرة",surahNum:2,ayahRef:"2:282",ayahAr:"يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا تَدَايَنتُم بِدَيْنٍ إِلَىٰ أَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّى فَاكْتُبُوهُ",ayahEn:"O you who have believed, when you contract a debt for a specified term, write it down.",ayahUr:"اے ایمان والو! جب تم ایک مقررہ مدت تک کے لیے قرض کا لین دین کرو تو اسے لکھ لو۔",companion:"Ibn Abbas (narrating the context; the verse was revealed at the Prophet's mosque market)",companionAr:"عبد الله بن عباس",companionRel:"Cousin of the Prophet ﷺ; greatest Quranic commentator of the first generation",story:`Ibn Abbas narrated: "This ayah — the longest single ayah in the entire Quran — was revealed regarding salam transactions (advance payment for deferred goods). When the Prophet ﷺ arrived in Medina, the people there were accustomed to making advance payments for dates deliverable 2–3 years later, without documentation. This led to frequent disputes. The Prophet ﷺ said 'Whoever does salam, let him specify the measure, weight, and term.' Then this ayah of 282 words came, laying down the entire law of financial documentation, witnessing, and obligation — the foundation of Islamic commercial law (fiqh al-mu'amalat) to this day.`,companionResponse:'Ibn Abbas emphasised: "Do not ask me why the longest ayah in Quran is about debt documentation. Allah knew that money is the greatest source of conflict among humans and gave it the most space." He taught this ayah extensively and is the principal narrator of its legal interpretation.',source:"Bukhari 2240; Abu Dawud 3463; Tafsir Ibn Abbas (Tanwir al-Miqbas)",category:"legal"},{id:20,surah:"At-Tawbah",surahAr:"التوبة",surahNum:9,ayahRef:"9:40",ayahAr:"إِلَّا تَنصُرُوهُ فَقَدْ نَصَرَهُ اللَّهُ إِذْ أَخْرَجَهُ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا ثَانِيَ اثْنَيْنِ إِذْ هُمَا فِي الْغَارِ إِذْ يَقُولُ لِصَاحِبِهِ لَا تَحْزَنْ إِنَّ اللَّهَ مَعَنَا",ayahEn:'If you do not aid him — Allah has already aided him when those who disbelieved had driven him out as one of two, when they were in the cave and he said to his companion, "Do not grieve; indeed Allah is with us."',ayahUr:"اگر تم اس کی مدد نہیں کرتے تو اللہ نے اس کی مدد کی تھی جب کافروں نے اسے نکال دیا تھا، جب وہ دونوں غار میں تھے اور وہ اپنے ساتھی سے کہہ رہا تھا: غم نہ کرو، اللہ ہمارے ساتھ ہے۔",companion:"Abu Bakr al-Siddiq",companionAr:"أبو بكر الصديق",companionRel:`The Prophet's closest companion; first Caliph; "the second of two" in this very ayah`,story:`During the Hijra to Medina (1 AH / 622 CE), the Prophet ﷺ and Abu Bakr hid in the Cave of Thawr for three days as Quraysh search parties combed the hills. At one point the search party came within feet of the cave entrance and Abu Bakr whispered in fear: "O Messenger of Allah, if they look at their feet they will see us!" The Prophet ﷺ replied calmly: "Lā tahzan, inna Allāha ma'ana" (Do not grieve; Allah is with us). Allah then sent a spider to spin a web and a pigeon to nest at the cave mouth, discouraging the searchers. Years later in Surah At-Tawbah, this private, intimate moment between two friends was immortalised in the Quran — making Abu Bakr the only companion explicitly mentioned in a Quranic verse by his relationship to the Prophet ﷺ ("his companion").`,companionResponse:'Abu Bakr later wept whenever he recited this ayah. He said: "On the day that verse was revealed about me, I felt that the honour was more than I deserved." Umar ibn al-Khattab, upon hearing Abu Bakr say this, said: "One night with Abu Bakr in that cave outweighs the deeds of the entire nation."',source:"Bukhari 3922; Muslim 2381; Tafsir al-Qurtubi 9:40",category:"personal"}],a=[{id:"all",label:"All"},{id:"personal",label:"Personal"},{id:"social",label:"Social"},{id:"legal",label:"Legal"},{id:"warfare",label:"Warfare"},{id:"family",label:"Family"},{id:"worship",label:"Worship"},{id:"doctrinal",label:"Doctrinal"}];export{e as Q,a};
